  Task 1: Scaffold and Explore the Angular Project
Goal: Create the Angular workspace and understand what each generated file does.
Steps:
1. Run ng new student-course-portal --routing --style=css. Accept defaults for all prompts.
2. Open the project in VS Code. For each of the following files, write a one-line comment in a notes.txt 
file explaining its purpose: angular.json, tsconfig.json, tsconfig.app.json, package.json, src/main.ts, 
src/app/app.module.ts (or app.config.ts in standalone mode), src/app/app.component.ts, 
src/index.html.
3. Run ng serve and open http://localhost:4200. Verify the default Angular welcome page loads.
4. Run ng build and inspect the dist/ folder. Note the generated files — identify which file contains the 
compiled application code.
5. In angular.json, locate the budgets configuration under architect > build > configurations > production. 
Note the maximumWarning and maximumError thresholds — document what these control.
Hint:
• Angular 17+ defaults to standalone components (no NgModules required). Angular 20 continues this 
pattern. If you see app.config.ts instead of app.module.ts, your project is using the standalone API — which 
is the modern approach.
• src/main.ts is the application entry point — it bootstraps either the AppModule or the root component 
directly.
Expected Outcome: ng serve runs without errors. notes.txt contains explanations for all 8 files. ng build 
produces a dist/ folder.
